passages.text: Whilst spreads ended the week largely unchanged from the previous week, it masked a moderate pick- up in market volatility. Spreads were not able to keep up with the midweek fall in US Treasuries yields, widening across the board, though recovered towards the latter part of the week. Indonesia and India HY underperformed, and a pick- up in primary market activity for Asia IG limited the scope for IG spread tightening. We maintain our preference for Asia IG over HY, and believe that a more defensive stance is warranted. In this week's Asia Credit Trader, we discuss:

Defensive stance calls for shifting Asia HY preference to Greater China HY. Given how tight valuation is across Asia credit, we see current levels providing little cushion against negative surprises. Recent news suggests that uncertainties surrounding Indonesia and India have increased, and we believe a neutral stance on Indonesia and India HY is warranted, and are shifting our Asia HY preference to Greater China HY.

Market focusing shifting from "US Exceptionalism" to "De- Dollarization". Late last year, much of the market attention was tilted towards "US Exceptionalism", though our investor conversations indicate that "De- Dollarization" has become a much bigger theme.

Structural factors boost Asia demand for foreign bonds. We expect Asia demand for foreign fixed income assets to remain firm, driven by a combination of structural current account surpluses and aging populations across the larger economies.

Taiwan and Japan insurers have reduced foreign bond buying. Whilst De- Dollarization has been a major theme in recent months, this has not been in 2025. Taiwan and Japan insurers have reduced foreign bond purchases since 2021.

USD credit still offers attractive yields. The USD- denominated bond market is by far the biggest and most liquid in the world, and offers yields above local currency bond yields from the larger Asian economies. Finding suitable domestic alternatives that offer yields similar to USD credit remains a challenge.

Local currency credit markets have room to grow, though USD bonds will continue to be important. Further "De- Dollarization" should provide ample opportunities for local currency credit markets to grow and develop, though we expect USD bonds will continue to be an important asset class for Asia credit investors for the foreseeable future.

Whilst spreads ended the week largely unchanged from the previous week, it masked a moderate pick up in market volatility. We began the week on a firm note, though spreads were not able to keep up with the midweek fall in US Treasuries yields, and widened across the board. The spread underperformance recovered towards the latter part of the week, but Indonesia and India HY underperformed, affected by news of domestic unrest and by tariff uncertainties, respectively. In addition, a pickup in primarymarket activity for Asia IG limited the scope for IG spread tightening. Given how tight valuation is, we see limited scope for further spread tightening. We, therefore, maintain our preference for Asia IG over HY, and believe that a more defensive stance is warranted.

Defensive stance calls for shifting Asia HY preference to Greater China HY. We shifted to a more positive stance on India and Indonesia HY in April, following their notable selloffs post the announcement of "Liberation Day" tariffs. Since then, India and Indonesia HY have recovered their spread widening and have performed well. Given how tight valuation is across Asia credit, we do not expect there to be much room for further spread tightening; rather, we see current levels providing little cushion against negative surprises. Recent new suggests that uncertainties surrounding Indonesia and India have increased, with domestic unrest in Indonesia and lingering tariff concerns for India. For these reasons, we believe a neutral stance on Indonesia and India HY is warranted, and we are shifting our Asia HY preference to Greater China HY.

Asia IG - prefer front end BBB and 7- 10yr A, with preference for bank capital securities over corporates. We prefer a neutral duration positioning to the index, with a preference for bank capital securities over corporates. We see the most value in BBB, specifically (1) HK Property BBB, (2) HK subordinated bank capital, and (3) the widest China IG names. For off- index positioning, we like HK Global Banks for AT1 securities and Australian Banks for Tier 2 bonds, and Japan insurance company subordinated bonds. Consider Indonesia 5yr Sovereign CDS and long/short opportunities in Japan corporate CDS for hedging.

Asia HY - search for carry in BB, though prefer IG over HY. We prefer BB over B, in line with our overall more defensive stance. We prefer Greater China BB corporates (including Property), as we believe China policymakers are focused on curbing tail risk. Amongst the frontier sovereigns, we prefer front- end Pakistan.

Market focus shifting from "US Exceptionalism" to "De- Dollarization". The past six months have seen noticeable shifts in focus from Asia credit investors. Late last year, much of the market attention was tilted towards "US Exceptionalism", as the strong Dollar, relatively high US rates and strong US equity performance led to fund flows being directed towards US assets. In recent months, investor conversations have indicated that "De- Dollarization" has become a much bigger theme, with many noting rising interest in non- USD assets and increased urgency in hedging USD FX exposures. There has been a rapid change in tone, but will this result in abrupt changes in investor behavior and asset allocation? As we discussed in a Global Markets Daily, we believe "De- Dollarization" will likely be a rising trend, though shifts in behavior by Asia credit investors is likely to be gradual.

Structural factors boost Asia demand for foreign bonds. A key reason why we expect changes in investors' allocation to be gradual is that demand for foreign fixed income assets has remained firm. Exhibit 1 plots the cumulative capital outflow into foreign bonds across Asia, including purchases by central banks, corporates, households and financial institutions. As the chart shows, such flows are dominated by the larger, more developed economies, namely Japan, Taiwan, Mainland China, Singapore, Hong Kong and Korea, whose purchases dwarf those of the rest. Asia combined. We believe structural reasons explain the rise in such purchases over the past two and a half decades. First, the larger, more developed economies run sizable current account surpluses, and, second, they are all experiencing aggregate populations. Combined, these factors create forces that should increase demand for foreign fixed income assets, and the slow- moving nature of demographic changes suggests that such demand is unlikely to abate in the near future.
Exhibit 1: The larger economies in Asia have been large buyers of foreign bonds Cumulative capital outflow into foreign bond markets to Dec 2024 (USD bn)
Source:IMF,CBC,MAS,Data compiled by Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Taiwan and Japan insurers have reduced foreign bond buying. Whilst De- Dollarization has been a major theme in recent months, this trend did not begin in 2025. For many years, Asian life insurers have been active buyers of USD bonds, as the USD credit market offers larger- sized deals and long duration assets that are less available in domestic markets. However, this trend has slowed, and in some cases reversed, since 2021. We note that foreign securities held by Taiwan insurance companies have hovered around USD700bn over the past 4 years after many years of steady increases (Exhibit 2), while foreign bonds held by Japan insurance companies have fallen from a peak of USD1trn at the end of March 2021 to USD741bn at the end of March 2025 (Exhibit 3).

We believe the reductions in foreign securities buying by Taiwan and Japan insurance companies were caused by two important factors. First, the hawkish turn by the Fed that began in 2022 led to sharp increases in the cost of FX hedges, which in turn led to reductions in foreign bond holdings; second, upward shifts in Japan government bond yields from late 2022 onward meant Japanese financial institutions were able to obtain sufficient yield from domestic securities, and can rely less on USD bonds. However, despite reduced reliance on foreign bonds in recent years, large positions are still maintained, with foreign securities representing around \(60\%\) of Taiwan insurance assets as of May 2025, and foreign bonds accounting for around \(25\%\) of Japan insurers' assets at the end of March this year. This illustrates that, while dependency on foreign bonds has decreased for these institutions, the lack of viable investment alternatives has meant USD bonds will likely continue to be an important asset class.
Exhibit 2: Insurance investments in foreign securities have stagnated in Taiwan... Foreign securities held by Taiwan insurance companies (USD bn)
Source: Taiwan Insurance Institute, Bloomberg, Data compiled by Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
Exhibit 3: ...and have fallen in Japan Foreign bonds held by Japan insurance companies (USD bn)
Source: Life Insurance Association of Japan, General Insurance Association of Japan, Bloomberg, Data compiled by Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

USD credit still offers attractive yields. While certain insurance funds in Asia have sought to maintain or lower their foreign bond exposures, this does not apply to all types of investors across the region. One example is to look at the amount of international bond funds purchased by Taiwan investors. As shown in Exhibit 4, this has risen by around USD50bn in the past three years to USD160bn, with higher US rates attracting interest from retail investors. This supports our expectation that shifts away from USD assets is a slow- moving train. The USD- denominated bond market is by far the biggest and most liquid in the world, and offers yields above local currency bond yields from the larger Asian economies. Therefore, finding suitable domestic alternatives that offer yields similar to USD credit remains a challenge.
Exhibit 4: High USD bond yields have attracted Taiwan retail demand Taiwan bond fund holdings of international bonds (USD bn)
Source: SITCA, Bloomberg, Data compiled by Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Local currency credit markets have room to grow, though USD bonds will continue to be important. With a weak Dollar one of our FX team's strongest views, we expect diversification away from USD will remain a recurring theme for Asia credit investors. This should pave the way for further growth in the local currency credit markets, and two areas that have become topical in recent months have been CNH and AUD bonds. This is reflected in the new issuance data: 2024 was a record year in CNH bond issuance (Exhibit 5) at RMB537bn (USD75bn) and in AUD bond issuance (Exhibit 6) at AUD70bn (USD45bn), and robust primary market activity so far this year. That said, except for the China domestic bond market, with around RMB188tn (USD26tn) outstanding, the size of local currency bond markets across Asia is noticeably smaller than the USD market. Looking ahead, further "De- Dollarization" should provide ample opportunities for local currency credit markets
to grow and develop, though we expect USD bonds will continue to be an important asset class for Asia credit investors for the foreseeable future.
Exhibit 5: 2024 a record year of issuance of CNH bonds... CNH Bond Issuance (RMB bn)
Exhibit 6: ...and for AUD bonds AUD fixed rate corporate and financial bond issuance (AUD bn)
Source: Bloomberg, Data compiled by Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
